{
  "id": "js-301",
  "name": "JavaScript 301 — Functional Programming Patterns",
  "description": "Deep dive into functional programming in JavaScript: pure functions, map/filter/reduce, closures, currying, function composition, immutability, and building a complete data transformation pipeline.",
  "created": "2026-03-29T00:00:00",
  "modified": "2026-03-29T00:00:00",
  "cells": [
    {
      "id": "js-301-intro",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "nodejs",
      "source": "# JavaScript 301 — Functional Programming Patterns\n\n**Functional Programming (FP)** is a programming paradigm that treats computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions, avoiding shared state and mutable data.\n\nJavaScript is a **multi-paradigm language** — you can mix OOP and FP styles. The FP parts of JavaScript are some of its most powerful and expressive features.\n\n## Core ideas\n| Concept | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Pure function** | Same input always gives same output. No side effects. |\n| **Immutability** | Don't modify data — create new data instead. |\n| **Higher-order functions** | Functions that take or return other functions. |\n| **Composition** | Build complex behavior by combining simple functions. |\n| **Currying** | Transform a multi-arg function into a chain of single-arg functions. |\n\n## Why bother?\n- Code is easier to **test** (pure functions have no hidden state)\n- Code is easier to **reason about** (no surprise mutations)\n- Highly **composable and reusable**\n- Works naturally with JavaScript's array methods",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
